\pard\s1\sb240\sa120{\b\fs44 Demonstration of DOCX support in calibre}\par
\pard\sa120 This document demonstrates the ability of the calibre DOCX Input plugin to convert the various typographic features in a Microsoft Word (2007 and newer) document. Convert this document to a modern ebook format, such as AZW3 for Kindles or EPUB for other ebook readers, to see it in action.\par
\pard\sa120 There is support for images, tables, lists, footnotes, endnotes, links, dropcaps and various types of text and paragraph level formatting.\par
\pard\sa120 To see the DOCX conversion in action, simply add this file to calibre using the {\rtlch\f1 \b \u8220?Add Books\u8221? \b0 }button and then click \u8220?{\rtlch\f1 \b Convert\u8221?. \b0 } Set the output format in the top right corner of the conversion dialog to EPUB or AZW3 and click {\rtlch\f1 \b \u8220?OK\u8221?\b0 }.\par
\pard\sa120 <a id="_Toc2054249818"></a>\par
\pard\s1\sb240\sa120{\b\fs44 {\rtlch\f1 \b Text Formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 <a id="_Toc2137712100"></a>\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\rtlch\f1 \b Inline formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 Here, we demonstrate various types of inline text formatting and the use of embedded fonts.\par
\pard\sa120 Here is some {\rtlch\f1 \b bold, \b0 }{\rtlch\f1 \i italic, \i0 }{\rtlch\f1 \b *bold-italic, \b0 }*{\rtlch\f1 \ul underlined \ul0 }and {\rtlch\f1 \strike struck out \strike0 } text. Then, we have a super{\rtlch\f1 script} and a sub{\rtlch\f1 script}. Now we see some red, green and blue text. Some text with a yellow highlight. Some text in a box. Some text in inverse video.\par
\pard\sa120 A paragraph with styled text: {\rtlch\f1 \i subtle emphasis  \i0 }followed by {\rtlch\f1 \b strong text \b0 }and {\rtlch\f1 \b *intense emphasis\b0 }*. This paragraph uses document wide styles for styling rather than inline text properties as demonstrated in the previous paragraph \u8212? calibre can handle both with equal ease.\par
\pard\sa120 <a id="_Toc1074133965"></a>\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\rtlch\f1 \b Fun with fonts\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120 This document has embedded the Ubuntu font family. The body text is in the Ubuntu typeface, here is some text in the Ubuntu Mono typeface, notice how every letter has the same width, even i and m. Every embedded font will automatically be embedded in the output ebook during conversion.\par
\pard\sa120 <a id="_Paragraph_level_formatting"></a><a id="_Toc2022725662"></a>\par
\pard\s2\sb240\sa120{\b\fs40 {\rtlch\f1 \b Paragraph level formatting\b0 }}\par
\pard\sa120\qr You can do crazy things with paragraphs, if the urge strikes you. For instance this paragraph is right aligned and has a right border. It has also been given a light gray background.\par
\pard\sa120 For the lovers of poetry amongst you, paragraphs with hanging indents, like this often come in handy. You can use hanging indents to ensure that a line of poetry retains its individual identity as a line even when the screen is  too narrow to display it as a single line. Not only does this paragraph have a hanging indent, it is also has an extra top margin, setting it apart from the preceding paragraph.\par
\pard\sa120 <a id="_Toc28114276"></a>\par
